Syringa pubescens is a specie of flowering plant in the lilac genus of the family Oleaceae , native to Korea and China ( Gansu , Hebei , Henan , Hubei , Jilin , Liaoning , Ningxia , Qinghai , Shaanxi , Shandong , Shanxi , Sichuan ) .Growing to 6 m ( 20 ft ) tall and broad , it is a substantial deciduous shrub with green leaf felted white beneath , and panicle of heavily scented , white-throated lilac flower in early summer.The specific epithet pubescens mean `` downy '' , referring to the texture of the leaves.Three subspecies ( formerly listed a separate specie ) are recognised : Syringa pubescens subsp .

Syringa reticulata ( Japanese tree lilac ; Chinese : 暴马丁香 bao ma ding xiang ; Japanese : ハシドイ , romanized : hashidoi ) is a specie of Lilac , native to eastern Asia : in northern Japan ( mainly Hokkaidō ) , northern China ( Gansu , Hebei , Heilongjiang , Henan , Jilin , Liaoning , Nei Mongol , Ningxia , Shaanxi , Shanxi , Sichuan ) , Korea , and far southeastern Russia ( Primorye ) .Syringa reticulata is a deciduous small tree growing to a height of 39 ' ( 12 m ) , rarely to 49 ' ( 15 m ) , with a trunk up to 11.8 '' ( 30 cm ) , rarely 15.7 '' ( 40 cm ) diameter ; it is the largest specie of lilac , and the only one that regularly make a small tree rather than a shrub .
